{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2a7b984d-dbc5-4c9c-a9d0-2481dc42076e","content":"In .NET MAUI, the app lifecycle moved from `Application` to the `Window` class. Override `CreateWindow` in your `App` class and hook into `Window` lifecycle events:\n\n```csharp\n// App.xaml.cs\nprotected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)\n{\n    var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);\n\n    window.Created  += (s, e) => { /* OnStart equivalent */ };\n    window.Resumed  += (s, e) => { /* OnResume equivalent */ };\n    window.Stopped  += (s, e) => { /* OnSleep equivalent */ };\n\n    // Also available:\n    // window.Activated, window.Deactivated,\n    // window.Backgrounding, window.Destroying\n\n    return window;\n}\n```\n\nAlternatively, subclass `Window` and override the corresponding methods (`OnCreated`, `OnResumed`, `OnStopped`, etc.) for cleaner separation.\n\n**Key mapping:**\n| Xamarin.Forms | MAUI Window event |\n|---|---|\n| `OnStart()` | `Created` |\n| `OnSleep()` | `Stopped` |\n| `OnResume()` | `Resumed` |\n\n> **Note:** `Application.OnStart`/`OnSleep`/`OnResume` still exist in MAUI for basic compat, but the `Window`-based approach is preferred since MAUI supports multiple windows.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e6af6600-4412-46b7-a85f-45909dfe514e","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating lifecycle methods from Xamarin.Forms to .NET MAUI. This is a knowledge question I can answer directly without needing to search the codebase.\n\nIn Xamarin.Forms, you'd override `OnStart()`, `OnSleep()`, and `OnResume()` on the `Application` class.\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the equivalent is to use the `Window` lifecycle events or override lifecycle methods on the `Window` class. Specifically:\n\n- `OnStart` → `Window.Created` event or override `Window.OnCreated()`\n- `OnSleep` → `Window.Backgrounding` event or override `Window.OnBackgrounding()`\n\n\n- `OnResume` → `Window.Resumed` event or override `Window.OnResumed()`\n\nWhile the old `Application` lifecycle methods still exist in .NET MAUI, the recommended approach is to use `Window` events instead, which include `Created`, `Activated`, and `Deactivated` for more granular control over the application lifecycle.\n\nThe `Window` class also provides `Stopped`, `Resumed`, `Destroying`, and `Backgrounding` events for handling additional lifecycle states. I can subscribe to these events by overriding `CreateWindow` in the `App` class or by creating a custom `Window` subclass.","outputTokens":761,"requestId":"A423:3AA73:5B95B37:641A667:69F00572"},"id":"4a8263f6-9422-4638-8f13-220df5aa1275","timestamp":"2026-04-28T00:55:28.995Z","parentId":"88412bd0-3f3f-46b9-bda9-013ad1bc9cf4"}
